“Idemia should not be contracted by IEBC to provide technology for elections in Kenya until it guarantees and it is confirmed by IEBC that the company has addressed the failures in its systems which led to the nullification of the 2017 presidential election,” said the Homabay Town MP.
But even as the MPs spoke, Idemia is already on the verge of being awarded a Sh10 billion tender for the supply of a technology to be used in the referendum for the planned constitutional amendment this year and the 2022 General Election.
Huduma Namba kits
Other than the election related contracts, the company was also hired in 2019 by the government to supply 31,500 biometric kits for the registration of Huduma Namba.
Nominated MP Godfrey Osotsi, an IT expert, said that election management in any country must be of the highest credibility and that Idemia is not ready to do that.
“It is not right for the IEBC to continue insisting on Idemia. The issues that informed the company’s debarment in the country are bare for all to see,” Mr Osotsi said.
Perhaps what could be the source of confusion and suspicion is the continued name change and rebranding by the company in the recent past.



