In 2013, the firm supplied the multi-billion shillings biometric voter registration (BVR) kits under Safran Morpho before changing to OT-Morpho during the 2017 elections.
In April 2019, the National Assembly adopted the amended report of the Public Accounts Committee (PAC) to block the French technology firm from doing business in the country for at least 10 years, citing a violation of the Companies Act.
In its findings, the watchdog committee chaired by Ugunja MP Opiyo Wandayi found the firm to have operated in the country illegally as it was not registered before doing business in Kenya, contrary to the companies’ law.
However, the firm successfully appealed against the resolution of the National Assembly at the High Court.
The High Court directed that the offensive recommendations against the firm be expunged from the report adopted by the House.
But the National Assembly has since appealed against the court judgment.
“For now I cannot say anything because the matter is in court. But as a committee we are in constant consultation with the lawyers representing the National Assembly in the appeal as we await the outcome,” Mr Wandayi said.
Local representatives
The Companies Act provides that before an entity does business in the country, it must be registered with the Registrar of Companies. Idemia, being a foreign company, was required to have its local representatives duly registered in the country.



